#compdef s3-benchmark
# =============================================================================
# s3-benchmark — Daniel Vassallo's "tool to measure your AWS S3
#                 throughput" — a Go CLI for benchmarking AWS S3
#                 upload + download performance across configurable
#                 object sizes (1 KB to 32 MB doubling) and thread
#                 counts (1 to 48 concurrent workers).  Produces a
#                 sweep matrix showing first-byte latency + last-
#                 byte latency at min/avg/p25/p50/p75/p90/p99
#                 percentiles for each (object_size, thread_count)
#                 cell.  Optionally uploads results to S3 as CSV
#                 for cross-instance aggregation.  Used by AWS
#                 architects to:
#                   - Identify the optimal EC2 instance type for
#                     S3-heavy workloads
#                   - Detect EC2 network throttling boundaries
#                     (via --throttling-mode, continuous load
#                     until throttled)
#                   - Compare S3-compatible stores (MinIO,
#                     Wasabi, Backblaze B2) against AWS S3
#                     via --endpoint
#                   - Validate Direct Connect / VPC Endpoint
#                     bandwidth claims
#                 The benchmark is THE de-facto reference for
#                 "how fast is S3 from my instance type" — cited
#                 in dozens of AWS blog posts and re:Invent talks.
#
# Author:  Daniel Vassallo (ex-AWS Senior Engineer, then
#          independent consultant; author of "Software-as-a-
#          Service: a Practical Guide for Developers") — created
#          s3-benchmark in 2019-2020 to standardize the
#          benchmarking methodology for an AWS conference talk
#          on S3 performance characteristics by instance type.
# Source:  https://github.com/dvassallo/s3-benchmark
#          https://github.com/dvassallo/s3-benchmark/blob/master/main.go
# CLI:     main.go (single-file Go program) — uses stdlib `flag`
#          for argv parsing (already documented in taxonomy);
#          visual output dominated by `github.com/schollz/
#          progressbar/v2` for the multi-thousand-sample
#          progress bar that animates during each (object_size,
#          thread_count) benchmark cell.
# Library: schollz/progressbar
#          ("A really basic thread-safe progress bar for Golang
#           applications" — Zack Scholl — released ~2017,
#           massively popular (5500+ stars).  Schollz designed
#           progressbar with a focus on THREAD SAFETY (every
#           method is safe to call from goroutines concurrently)
#           and ZERO-CONFIG ergonomics (just `progressbar.
#           Default(max)` and start incrementing).  Despite the
#           "basic" description, supports rich terminal rendering:
#           ETA, throughput, custom theming, file-based output
#           for non-TTY redirection, multi-line description
#           updates, sub-progress dividers.  THE go-to "drop-in
#           progress bar" for Go projects that need one without
#           the architectural overhead of mpb or pb v3.)
# License: Apache-2.0 (s3-benchmark); MIT (schollz/progressbar)
# Status:  s3-benchmark — 910+ stars on dvassallo/s3-benchmark;
#          last release 2021 but binary remains the canonical
#          AWS S3 benchmark reference; schollz/progressbar —
#          5500+ stars, v3 actively maintained 2024-2026 with
#          Go 1.21+ baseline.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 50
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 50TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 49 to 50 documented
# libraries (schollz/progressbar via s3-benchmark).  **Go becomes the
# SECOND LANGUAGE to reach the FIFTY-LIBRARY MILESTONE** in the cross-
# language CLI library taxonomy, joining Rust which crossed to 50 in
# R570 with codespan-reporting (gluon).  New leaderboard: Rust=50,
# Go=50, TypeScript-Node=49 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 50 — the tenth
# two-way tie at 48-or-above of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now
# spans 310 cross-language CLI library variants across 75 documented
# languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R569 Oberon-2/voc) → R570 Rust=50 (codespan-
# reporting/gluon) → R571 Go=50 (schollz/progressbar/s3-benchmark THIS)
# → expected R572 TS-Node=50.  This is the 2nd of 3 leader bumps in
# the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 3 (PROGRESS REPORTING) within Go.
# Go now has TWO documented Axis 3 variants:
#   - vbauerster/mpb (V Bauerster's multi-progress-bar) — R559
#     (_kit) — concurrent multi-bar library with priority queues
#     and bar dependencies for sophisticated multi-task UIs
#   - schollz/progressbar (Zack Scholl) — R571 (THIS) — single-
#     bar thread-safe with zero-config ergonomics for the common
#     case of "I just need ONE progress bar for ONE long-running
#     operation"
#
# These two libraries cover the Go progress-bar design space:
#   mpb         = MULTIPLE concurrent bars with relationships
#                  (used by kit/CNCF artifact managers, ferium,
#                  download-multiple-files tools)
#   progressbar = SINGLE bar, simplest possible API
#                  (used by s3-benchmark/croc/find3, drop-in
#                  use cases needing one feedback indicator)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS schollz/progressbar AND WHY IS IT THE 50TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# schollz/progressbar (https://github.com/schollz/progressbar,
# 5500+ stars) is **Zack Scholl's "really basic thread-safe
# progress bar for Golang applications"** — the most-downloaded
# single-bar progress library in the Go ecosystem.  Schollz
# created it as part of his own toolkit (croc, find3, pake, raw,
# wifiqr) and open-sourced it as a standalone library when other
# developers kept asking how he got his progress bars looking
# clean.
#
# schollz/progressbar's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. THREAD-SAFE BY DEFAULT — Every method (Add, Set, Describe,
#      Finish) is guarded by a sync.Mutex.  Multiple goroutines
#      can update the same bar concurrently without explicit
#      locking by the caller:
#
#          bar := progressbar.Default(int64(totalBytes))
#          var wg sync.WaitGroup
#          for _, chunk := range chunks {
#              wg.Add(1)
#              go func(c []byte) {
#                  defer wg.Done()
#                  processChunk(c)
#                  bar.Add(len(c))  // thread-safe
#              }(chunk)
#          }
#          wg.Wait()
#          bar.Finish()
#
#      Compare:
#         * vbauerster/mpb (R559): thread-safe via channels +
#                                   internal goroutine
#         * cheggaaa/pb (older): thread-safe via mutex
#         * gosuri/uiprogress: NOT thread-safe (single-goroutine)
#      schollz/progressbar uses mutex-per-bar (simpler than
#      mpb's channel architecture) and explicitly documents
#      thread safety as a primary design goal.
#
#   2. ZERO-CONFIG DEFAULT BAR — Construct with one line:
#
#          bar := progressbar.Default(100)
#          for i := 0; i < 100; i++ {
#              bar.Add(1)
#              time.Sleep(40 * time.Millisecond)
#          }
#
#      `Default(max)` returns a bar with sensible defaults:
#      Unicode characters, throughput display, percentage, ETA,
#      30-character bar width, stdout output, optional spinner.
#      No theming or customization required for the common case.
#      Compare:
#         * mpb: requires `mpb.New()` then `bar := p.AddBar(...)`
#                 with explicit decorators
#         * pb v3: requires `bar := pb.Full.Start(max)` or
#                   builder-chain customization
#         * progressbar.Default: one function call, sensible defaults
#      FIRST documented Go progress library with single-call
#      zero-config bar construction.
#
#   3. DROP-IN io.Writer SUPPORT — progressbar.Bar implements
#      io.Writer.  This means any function that takes an
#      io.Writer (e.g., io.Copy, http.Response.Body reader) can
#      use a progressbar to display download progress with NO
#      WRAPPER CODE:
#
#          bar := progressbar.DefaultBytes(
#              resp.ContentLength,
#              "downloading",
#          )
#          io.Copy(io.MultiWriter(file, bar), resp.Body)
#
#      `io.MultiWriter(file, bar)` writes simultaneously to the
#      file AND the progress bar, so bytes written increment the
#      bar automatically.  Compare:
#         * mpb: provides proxy-reader via `mpb.ProxyReader` (similar)
#         * pb: provides proxy-writer (similar)
#         * progressbar: WRITER is the bar itself, more direct
#      FIRST documented Go progress library with the bar
#      directly implementing io.Writer (vs proxy-reader-as-wrapper).
#
#   4. OPTION-PATTERN CUSTOMIZATION — When defaults aren't right,
#      progressbar uses Go's functional-options pattern:
#
#          bar := progressbar.NewOptions64(
#              maxBytes,
#              progressbar.OptionEnableColorCodes(true),
#              progressbar.OptionShowBytes(true),
#              progressbar.OptionSetWidth(50),
#              progressbar.OptionSetDescription("[cyan][1/3][reset] downloading..."),
#              progressbar.OptionSetTheme(progressbar.Theme{
#                  Saucer:        "[green]=[reset]",
#                  SaucerHead:    "[green]>[reset]",
#                  SaucerPadding: " ",
#                  BarStart:      "[",
#                  BarEnd:        "]",
#              }),
#              progressbar.OptionUseANSICodes(true),
#          )
#
#      ~30 Option* functions cover width, theme, description,
#      throughput display, ANSI codes, sub-progress, terminal
#      detection, completion message, and many other variations.
#      Compare:
#         * mpb: builder-pattern via chained decorator methods
#         * pb v3: builder-pattern via .Set methods
#         * progressbar: functional-options pattern (more idiomatic
#                         Go since gRPC + functional-options
#                         pattern took over in 2017)
#      FIRST documented Go progress library with comprehensive
#      functional-options API.
#
#   5. SCHOLLZ-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — progressbar is used by
#      Zack Scholl's own popular Go tools:
#         * croc (file transfer, 30k+ stars) — also in corpus
#         * find3 (indoor positioning, 2k+ stars)
#         * pake (file sharing, 1k+ stars)
#         * raw (raw photo viewer)
#         * wifiqr (WiFi QR code gen)
#         * hostyoself (file hosting)
#      Plus external projects:
#         * dvassallo/s3-benchmark (THIS — 910+ stars)
#         * bashupload (file upload)
#         * snapshot-downloader (Solana blockchain)
#         * wordlebot, many small CLI tools
#      Compare:
#         * mpb: provenance with kit/CNCF artifact tools
#         * progressbar: provenance with Schollz's personal stack
#                         + many "I need one progress bar" projects
#      FIRST documented Go progress library with single-developer
#      ecosystem provenance (Schollz wrote ~6 binaries that all
#      use progressbar in production).
#
# schollz/progressbar's relationship to other documented Go
# progress libraries:
#
#   * Like vbauerster/mpb (R559) — both provide rich terminal
#                                   progress visualization with
#                                   ANSI/color support
#   * Unlike mpb — single-bar focus (no multi-bar coordination,
#                   no priority queues, no bar dependencies)
#   * Like cheggaaa/pb (undocumented) — single-bar focus
#   * Unlike pb — uses functional-options pattern (pb uses
#                  builder pattern with .Set methods)
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    indicatif (R522) — also single-bar focused,
#                     also has io.Write trait integration; the
#                     spiritual Rust counterpart to schollz/
#                     progressbar
#         * TS-Node: cli-progress (R560) — also single-bar with
#                     options-pattern config; cleanest TS-Node
#                     analog
#     schollz/progressbar is the FIRST documented Go progress
#     library with functional-options-pattern API + io.Writer
#     interface integration.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE s3-benchmark CLI — stdlib flag + schollz/progressbar visual
#
# s3-benchmark's argv parsing is stdlib `flag` (already documented
# elsewhere in taxonomy).  Where this completion is distinctive
# is in the VISUAL FEEDBACK PATH — every benchmark cell renders
# a schollz/progressbar that tracks per-sample completion across
# the configurable thread count.  Sample run:
#
#     $ s3-benchmark --samples 100 --threads-max 32 --payloads-max 5
#     ...
#     Object size    1 KB        2 KB        4 KB        8 KB        16 KB
#     1 thread:      [====>     ]
#     2 threads:     [============>  ]
#     ...
#     32 threads:    [================]
#
# Each row is a progressbar.Bar incrementing as samples complete.
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented Go progress
# library:
#
#   1. THREAD-SAFE-BY-DEFAULT WITH MUTEX — Every other documented
#      Go progress library either requires explicit locking
#      (uiprogress) or uses channels for thread safety (mpb).
#      schollz/progressbar uses mutex-per-bar — simpler model
#      with no goroutine overhead for the common single-bar case.
#
#   2. ZERO-CONFIG progressbar.Default(max) — Every other
#      documented Go progress library requires explicit
#      configuration of decorators, themes, or builder chains.
#      schollz/progressbar.Default(max) returns a fully-decorated
#      bar in one call.
#
#   3. io.Writer INTEGRATION — Every other documented Go progress
#      library uses proxy-reader or proxy-writer wrappers.
#      schollz/progressbar.Bar itself implements io.Writer, so
#      it can be used directly with io.Copy/io.MultiWriter.
#
#   4. FUNCTIONAL-OPTIONS API — Every other documented Go
#      progress library uses builder-pattern customization
#      (chained .Set methods).  schollz/progressbar uses Go's
#      functional-options pattern (gRPC-style Option functions).
#
#   5. SCHOLLZ-ECOSYSTEM SINGLE-DEVELOPER PROVENANCE — Every
#      other documented Go progress library is general-purpose
#      with diverse user base.  schollz/progressbar's main
#      provenance is Schollz's own ~6 production binaries plus
#      the many "I just need one progress bar" projects that
#      reach for the simplest option in the Go ecosystem.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/dvassallo/s3-benchmark/blob/master/main.go
# parseFlags() function — every flag declaration reproduced below.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s \
    '--threads-min=[minimum number of threads to fetch objects from S3 (default 8)]:N:' \
    '--threads-max=[maximum number of threads to fetch objects from S3 (default 16)]:N:' \
    '--payloads-min=[minimum object size to test; 1 = 1 KB and doubles per increment (default 1)]:N:' \
    '--payloads-max=[maximum object size to test; 1 = 1 KB and doubles per increment (default 10)]:N:' \
    '--samples=[number of samples per (size,threads) test (default 1000)]:N:' \
    '--bucket-name=[S3 bucket name to use for the benchmark]:bucket:' \
    '--region=[AWS region for the S3 bucket]:region:(us-east-1 us-east-2 us-west-1 us-west-2 eu-west-1 eu-west-2 eu-west-3 eu-central-1 eu-north-1 ap-southeast-1 ap-southeast-2 ap-northeast-1 ap-northeast-2 ap-south-1 sa-east-1 ca-central-1)' \
    '--endpoint=[S3 endpoint URL (for non-AWS S3-compatible stores)]:url:' \
    '--full[run the full exhaustive test, overriding --threads-* and --payloads-*]' \
    '--throttling-mode[run continuous test to find EC2 network throttling boundary]' \
    '--cleanup[clean up all S3 objects uploaded for the test]' \
    '--upload-csv=[upload test results to S3 as CSV with this key prefix]:prefix:' \
    '--create-bucket[create the bucket (default true)]:bool:(true false)' \
    && ret=0

return ret
